==Promotion==
The [[Weinstein Co]]. commissioned three murals to be painted in Los Angeles, New York and San Francisco by well-known street artists [[Ron English (artist)|Ron English]], [[Lydia Emily]] and [[LNY]], in anticipation of the film.<ref>{{cite web|last=Vankin|first=Deborah|title=Street artist murals to promote 'Fruitvale Station' hit some walls|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-ca-lahoda-sidebar-fruitvale-20130707,0,852784.story|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=July 21, 2013|date=July 4, 2013}}</ref>

Some people questioned having a poster for the film in Fruitvale Station, but a BART spokeswoman said about this decision: 
<blockquote>"there was no debate whether to allow ''Fruitvale Station'' [advertisements] on BART. None whatsoever. We really support Ryan. He's just an amazing person. . . . I think that Ryan had said it was his intention to show his love for Oakland and the people of Oakland, and he really succeeded."<ref>{{cite web|last=Hartlaub|first=Peter|title=There<U+2019>s a <U+201C>Fruitvale Station<U+201D> movie poster at Fruitvale Station|url=http://blog.sfgate.com/thebigevent/2013/07/10/theres-a-fruitvale-station-movie-poster-at-fruitvale-station/|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|accessdate=July 20, 2013|date=July 10, 2013}}</ref></blockquote>

Promotional material used on the film's Facebook page and website referred to the controversial [[shooting of Trayvon Martin]] in Florida, which was in the news at the same time as the film's release.<ref>{{cite web|last=Pond|first=Steve|title='Fruitvale Station' and Trayvon Martin Murder Case: Art and Life Collide on Eve of Film Release|url=http://www.thewrap.com/movies/column-post/fruitvale-station-and-trayvon-martin-murder-case-art-and-life-collide-eve-film-release-1|work=The Wrap|accessdate=|date=July 10, 2013}}</ref> This drew some criticism, with publicist Angie Meyer stating, "It's absolutely inappropriate and morally wrong to use a high profile case to create publicity and buzz around a movie release."<ref>{{cite web|title='Fruitvale Station' criticized for fictional scene, marketing tied to George Zimmerman trial|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/celebrities/ci_23648824/fruitvale-station-criticized-fictional-scene-marketing-tied-George|work=[[San Jose Mercury News]]|accessdate=|date=July 12, 2013}}</ref> 

As part of its film promotion, the Weinstein Co. set up the "I am __" campaign to encourage people to share stories of overcoming acts of social injustice or mistreatment, and to upload photos or other artworks related to those experiences.<ref name="LAT2">{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Chris|title=Weinstein Co. uses social justice campaign to promote 'Fruitvale Station'|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-weinstein-co-uses-social-justice-campaign-to-promote-fruitvale-station-20130717,0,3544023.story|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=July 20, 2013|date=July 17, 2013}}</ref>

==Release==
''Fruitvale Station'' [[Film premiere|premiered]] on January 19, 2013 during the [[2013 Sundance Film Festival]] where it was listed as ''Fruitvale'' before undergoing a title change.<ref name="name change">{{cite web|last=Olsen|first=Mark|title=Sundance winner 'Fruitvale' changes name to 'Fruitvale Station'|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/apr/17/entertainment/la-et-mn-sundance-winner-fruitvale-changes-trains-to-fruitvale-station-20130417|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=July 20, 2013|date=April 17, 2013}}</ref> After premiering at Sundance, the film was at the center of a distribution bidding war. Rights for the film were ultimately acquired by [[The Weinstein Company]] for approximately US$2 million.<ref name="HR">{{cite web|last=Fleming|first=Mike|title=Sundance: The Weinstein Company Acquires <U+2018>Fruitvale<U+2019>|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/01/fruitvale-sundance-film-festival-dea-weinstein/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=January 16, 2013|date=January 21, 2013}}</ref> In May 2013, ''Fruitvale Station'' appeared in the [[Un Certain Regard]], an award section recognizing unique and innovative films, at the [[2013 Cannes Film Festival|66th Cannes Film Festival]]<ref name="Cannes2013">{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.fr/en/article/59652.html |title=2013 Official Selection|date=18 April 2013|accessdate=18 April 2013|work=Cannes}}</ref> and won the award for Best First Film.<ref name="HWR-UCR">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cannes-missing-picture-wins-regard-558551 |title=Cannes: 'The Missing Picture' Wins Un Certain Regard Prize |date=26 May 2013|accessdate=26 May 2013|work=Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>

The Oakland premiere was held as a private screening at Grand Lake Theater on June 20, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Oscar Grant Film <U+2018>Fruitvale Station<U+2019> Premieres In Oakland|url=http://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2013/06/20/oscar-grant-film-fruitvale-station-premieres-in-oakland/|work=CBS San Francisco|accessdate=July 20, 2013|date=June 20, 2013}}</ref> The film opened in select theaters on July 12.<ref>{{cite web|last=Duckworth|first=Anna|title=Oscar Grant Movie <U+2018>Fruitvale Station<U+2019> Premieres To Sellout Crowds|url=http://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2013/07/12/oscar-grant-movie-fruitvale-station-premieres-to-sellout-crowds/|work=CBS San Francisco|accessdate=July 20, 2013|date=July 12, 2013}}</ref> This opening took place about the same time as the Florida jury decided [[State of Florida v. George Zimmerman|the verdict in the trial of George Zimmerman for shooting Trayvon Martin]].<ref name="LAT2"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Specialty Box Office: <U+2018>Fruitvale Station<U+2019> Is A Hit; Sundance Winner Opens With Parallels To Trayvon Martin Case|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/07/specialty-box-office-fruitvale-station-michael-b-jordan-trayvon-martin/|work=''Deadline.com''|accessdate=July 20, 2013|date=July 14, 2013}}</ref>

===Box office===
The film grossed an estimated $127,445 on its first night<ref>{{cite web|last=Wood|first=Mikael|title='Fruitvale Station' sells out screenings in Oakland|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-fruitvale-station-sells-out-screenings-in-oakland-20130713,0,6711442.story|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=July 20, 2013|date=July 13, 2013}}</ref> and ended its first weekend of limited release with $377,285 from 7 theaters for a $53,898 per-theater-average.<ref>{{cite web|last=Knegt|first=Peter|title=Specialty Box Office: 'Fruitvale Station' Huge In Limited Debut; 'Way, Way Back' Expands Strong|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/specialty-box-office-fruitvale-station-huge-in-limited-debut-way-way-back-expands-strong|work=[[IndieWire]]|accessdate=July 20, 2013|date=July 14, 2013}}</ref> It is the third highest opening of the year for a film in limited release (behind ''[[Spring Breakers]]'' and ''[[The Place Beyond the Pines]]'')<ref>{{cite web|last=Brueggemann|first=Tom|title=Arthouse Audit: 'Fruitvale Station' Makes Strong Opening Statement; 'Way Way Back' Builds Steam|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/fruitvale-station-makes-strong-opening-statement|work=[[IndieWire]]|accessdate=August 19, 2013|date=July 14, 2013}}</ref> and it is also one of the best openings for a Sundance festival top prize winner.<ref>{{cite web|last=Knegt|first=Peter|title=Box Office: How Did 'Fruitvale Station'{{'s}} Opening Hold Up Against Past Sundance Jury Prize Winners?|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/box-office-how-did-fruitvale-stations-opening-hold-up-against-past-sundance-jury-prize-winners|work=IndieWire|accessdate=July 20, 2013|date=July 15, 2013}}</ref> A week after its debut, ''Fruitvale Station'' expanded to 35 theaters and garnered $742,272 for $21,832 per-screen average.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Week After Trayvon Martin Verdict, 'Fruitvale Station' Strong at Box Office|url=http://www.thewrap.com/movies/article/week-after-trayvon-martin-verdict-fruitvale-station-strong-box-office-104786|work=The Wrap|accessdate=July 21, 2013|date=July 21, 2013}}</ref> The film opened nationwide on July 26 in more than 1000 locations.<ref>{{cite web|last=McClintock|first=Pamela|title=Movies Stake Out Strategic Release Dates as Next Awards Season Takes Shape|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/movies-stake-strategic-release-dates-431656|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=July 20, 2013|date=March 29, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Subers|first=Ray|title=Forecast: 'Wolverine' To Go Berserk On Box Office This Weekend|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3705&p=.htm|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=July 26, 2013|date=July 25, 2013}}</ref> It ranked #10 at the box office, earning $4.59 million.<ref>{{cite web|last=Subers|first=Ray|title=Weekend Report: 'Wolverine' Bleeds, But Still Easily Leads|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3706&p=.htm|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=July 31, 2013|date=July 28, 2013}}</ref> The film has grossed $16,101,339 in the United States and $340,821 elsewhere, for a worldwide total of $16,442,160.<ref name="BOM"/>

===Critical reception===
''Fruitvale Station'' has received widespread critical acclaim. The film holds a 92% approval rating on aggregate review site [[Rotten Tomatoes]] with an average score of 8.2/10, based on 157 reviews. The site's critical consensus reads: "Passionate and powerfully acted, ''Fruitvale Station'' serves as a celebration of life, a condemnation of death, and a triumph for star Michael B. Jordan."<ref>{{cite web|title=Fruitvale Station (2013)|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/fruitvale_station/|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Flixter]]|accessdate=January 14, 2014}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[weighted mean]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the film received an average score of 85, based on 43 reviews, indicating "universal acclaim".<ref name="Metacritic">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/fruitvale-station|title=Fruitvale Station|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=July 27, 2013}}</ref> [[CinemaScore]] reported that audiences gave an "A" average grade.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kaufman|first=Amy|title='Fruitvale' starts strong, may benefit from Zimmerman acquittal|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-fruitvale-station-box-office-zimmerman-acquittal-20130714,0,3507189.story|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=July 26, 2013|date=July 14, 2013}}</ref> [[Todd McCarthy]] of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' called it "a compelling debut" and "a powerful dramatic feature film". He also praised the lead performances stating, "As Oscar, Jordan at moments gives off vibes of a very young [[Denzel Washington]] in the way he combines gentleness and toughness; he effortlessly draws the viewer in toward him. Diaz is vibrant as his patient and loyal girlfriend, while Spencer brings her gravitas to the proceedings as his stalwart mother."<ref>{{cite web|last=McCarthy|first=Todd|title=Fruitvale: Sundance Review|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movie/fruitvale/review/414010|publisher=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=January 31, 2013|date=January 20, 2013}}</ref>

Actor [[Joseph Gordon-Levitt]] has praised the film as the "best film" of Sundance Film Festival 2013.<ref>@hitRECordJoe Twitter status. "[https://twitter.com/hitRECordJoe/status/355810036288724992 I said it at @SundanceFest and I'll say it again: FRUITVALE STATION should win Best Picture next year. It opens today, go see it..]" Twitter. Posted July 12, 2013. Retrieved July 15, 2013.</ref>

In writing for ''[[The Village Voice]]'', chief film critic Stephanie Zacharek called it "a restrained but forceful picture that captures some of the texture and detail of one human life" and praised first-time director [[Ryan Coogler]], writing that he "dramatizes Oscar's last day by choosing ''not'' to dramatize it: The events unfold casually, without any particular scheme. And yet because we know how this story will end, there's a shivery, understated tension running beneath."<ref>[http://www.villagevoice.com/2013-07-10/film/fruitvale-station/ "A Shivery, Understated Tension Runs Through ''Fruitvale Station''"], ''[[The Village Voice]]'', July 20, 2013. Retrieved on July 12, 2013.</ref>

In his Sundance festival wrap up, critic [[Kenneth Turan]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' said of ''Fruitvale Station'', "Made with assurance and quiet emotion, this unexpectedly devastating drama based on the real life 2009 shooting of an unarmed young black man at an Oakland Fruitvale Station of BART (San Francisco Bay Area Transit Fruitvale Station) impressed everyone as the work of an exceptional filmmaker." <ref>{{cite web|last=Turan|first=Kenneth|title=The Sundance Film Festival Proves again to be a mixed bag...|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/moviesnow/la-et-mn-sundance-kenny-20130128,0,3082363.story|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=January 31, 2013|date=January 28, 2013}}</ref>

In a more mixed review, Geoff Berkshire of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called it "a well-intentioned attempt to put a human face on the tragic headlines surrounding Oscar Grant." Though he praised Michael B. Jordan's performance, he critiqued the "relentlessly positive portrayal" of the film's subject: "Best viewed as an ode to victim's rights, ''Fruitvale'' forgoes nuanced drama for heart-tugging, head-shaking and rabble-rousing."<ref name="Variety"/>

In his negative ''[[New York Post]]'' review and subsequent [[Fact checker]] article in ''[[Forbes]]'', [[Kyle Smith]] concluded that Coogler omits key information, while fabricating other scenes, in order to manipulate viewers into a distorted impression of what happened.<ref>{{cite web|last=Smith|first=Kyle|title='Fruitvale Station' tells some, omits some|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/movies/sour_squishy_fruitvale_IKOntZsaTW6FqgMGLxvIJO?utm_medium=rss&utm_content=Movies|work=[[New York Post]]|accessdate=|date=July 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Smith|first=Kyle|title='Fruitvale Station' Is Loose With The Facts In An Effort To Elicit Sympathy For Oscar Grant|url=http://www.forbes.com/sites/kylesmith/2013/07/25/fruitvale-station-is-loose-with-the-facts-in-an-effort-to-elicit-sympathy-for-oscar-grant/|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=|date=July 25, 2013}}</ref>

The film appeared on several critics' top ten lists of the best films of 2013:<ref>{{cite web|last=Dietz|first=Jason|title=2013 Film Critic Top Ten Lists|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critic-top-10-lists-best-movies-of-2013|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=December 25, 2013}}</ref>
* 3rd <U+2013>  Betsy Sharkey, ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''
* 3rd <U+2013> Mara Reinstein, ''[[Us Weekly]]''
* 4th <U+2013> [[Owen Gleiberman]], ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''
* 4th <U+2013> Chris Nashawaty, ''Entertainment Weekly''
* 5th <U+2013> [[Michael Phillips (critic)|Michael Phillipps]], ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''
* 8th <U+2013> Joe Neumaier, ''[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]''
* 9th <U+2013> Ann Hornaday ''[[The Washington Post]]''
* 9th <U+2013> Randy Myers, ''[[San Jose Mercury News]]''
* 9th <U+2013> [[Anne Thompson (film critic)|Anne Thompson]]
* No rank <U+2013> [[Kenneth Turan]], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''
* No rank <U+2013> [[Carrie Rickey]] 
* No rank <U+2013> [[Jonathan Rosenbaum]]

